anonymously too. And I've shown that Slido link here on the screen. But thank you again for

00:00:57.439 --> 00:01:06.480
joining us and I'll turn it over to Joe. Hi, I'm Joe Roberts and I'm a product manager here

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:12.400
at Posit. And one of the most common questions I get asked, especially by IT administrators and

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:18.239
security teams, is how to make sure the public packages that their data scientists want to use

00:01:18.239 --> 00:01:24.559
are safe. So today we're going to explore that topic. And we're going to start with an overview

00:01:24.639 --> 00:01:29.839
of the main public package repositories used by data scientists working in R and Python

00:01:30.559 --> 00:01:36.000
to understand how they work, and more importantly, how they differ in their approaches to package

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.839
publishing. We'll also explore some of the more common types of security risks in using public

00:01:41.839 --> 00:01:47.919
packages. And we'll look at strategies to mitigate those risks using tools like Posit Package Manager.

00:01:48.559 --> 00:01:54.959
So let's get started. And let's take a look at the main public package repositories for data science.

00:01:56.959 --> 00:02:05.120
CRAN is the primary repository for R packages. Bioconductor is also widely used for R packages,

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:12.320
primarily in data science and life sciences. And on the Python side, the Python Package Index,

00:02:12.320 --> 00:02:20.240
or PyPI. CRAN and Bioconductor take a similar approach to packages. And if you've ever submitted

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:25.119
a package to be published on CRAN, you know exactly how stringent those requirements are.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:31.119
Each package has to pass a comprehensive set of checks to ensure the package is properly formed

00:02:31.119 --> 00:02:37.759
and documented, builds properly, doesn't cause any other packages to fail. Most importantly,

00:02:37.839 --> 00:02:42.559
from a security standpoint, these packages must be submitted entirely as source code so there's

00:02:42.559 --> 00:02:49.520
full transparency of what is contained within the package, and it will go through an actual

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:55.199
human verification before being published. It's like the exclusive club with the bouncer out front,

00:02:55.199 --> 00:02:59.440
where they may not make sure you can dance, but they definitely are going to make sure you're

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:05.119
well-dressed before letting you in. In contrast, PyPI takes the opposite approach.

00:03:05.679 --> 00:03:12.160
PyPI is much more like Wikipedia, a completely open repository where anyone can create an account

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:20.320
and publish packages. Both in source or binary packages, which then become instantly available

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:26.800
to everyone around the world. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, as it does make a far

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:31.919
wider array of packages available, though it does pose some additional security risks that we'll

00:03:31.919 --> 00:03:38.960
have to take a closer look at. So let's start with the security risks now, and the first security

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:46.880
risk is around the more fundamental question of package quality, or does this package accurately

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:52.639
do what it claims to do? And that's not always an easy question to answer, especially if you're

00:03:52.639 --> 00:03:57.039
not a domain expert, but there are some other more objective factors you can look at to help

00:03:57.039 --> 00:04:02.080
you assess quality. Things like the number of package downloads, or how many other people are

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:07.759
using this package, the author's reputation, is this package author well known in the community,

00:04:07.759 --> 00:04:14.559
do they have a lot of other well-used packages that they've published, is this package well

00:04:14.559 --> 00:04:19.600
documented, are there the functions documented, are there instructional guides, vignettes, or other

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:27.119
tutorials available, and how frequently is the package updated, when was the last update,

00:04:27.119 --> 00:04:33.600
is it actively maintained and frequently updated with fixes, and finally, I mean, does the

00:04:34.239 --> 00:04:38.880
package include a comprehensive set of tests to verify that the functionality is working correctly?

00:04:41.359 --> 00:04:46.959
So how do we mitigate package quality concerns? Well, the obvious option is for someone to

00:04:46.959 --> 00:04:52.079
carefully scrutinize the package and make a determination, but as we pointed out earlier,

00:04:52.079 --> 00:04:57.920
that's not always easy. Fortunately, the community has developed some tools to help

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:03.279
with those assessments. For example, our friends over at the R Validation Hub have produced an R

00:05:03.279 --> 00:05:08.880
package called Risk Metric that takes these that I just talked about and many more quality metrics

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:15.519
into account to help you get an objective assessment of package quality. And once you've

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:19.839
done your reviews and done your assessments and decided which packages you want to allow

00:05:19.839 --> 00:05:25.359
your data scientists to use, you can leverage a feature in Posit Package Manager called curated

00:05:25.359 --> 00:05:31.679
repositories, allowing you to create a separate repository just containing the CRAN or PyPI

00:05:31.679 --> 00:05:35.040
packages that you've approved for use in your team or organization.

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:43.040
So next let's talk about what you typically think of when you say security, and that's

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:49.040
vulnerabilities. And these can occur at any point in the package, from the source code

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:55.119
introduced in compiled code or vulnerabilities that exist in external libraries that are used

00:05:55.119 --> 00:06:00.079
by the package. And it's important to note that while these are sometimes malicious,

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:07.119
most often these are just due to mistakes in poorly written code. But they're still just

00:06:07.119 --> 00:06:14.320
as important to assess and resolve. So mitigating vulnerabilities is actually a little bit easier

00:06:14.320 --> 00:06:18.799
for public packages, and that's because the packages are known published quantities.

00:06:18.799 --> 00:06:23.200
You don't generally need to worry about scanning them yourself because numerous others are scanning

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:29.839
these already published packages and reporting any vulnerabilities on them. So the best resource

00:06:29.839 --> 00:06:35.839
for mitigating those are through databases of known vulnerabilities. In CRAN's case,

00:06:35.839 --> 00:06:41.040
there are relatively few vulnerabilities reported, partially due to that strong curation of packages

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:45.920
due to the bouncer of the door. But Posit has recently started working with the R Consortium

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:51.440
on building out an advisory database to track known vulnerabilities in a standardized format

00:06:51.440 --> 00:06:56.160
that was first adopted by the widely used Python Packaging Advisory Database that's

00:06:56.160 --> 00:07:03.119
maintained by the Python Packaging Authority. Both of these now feed into the OSV open source

00:07:03.119 --> 00:07:11.200
vulnerability database that was created by Google and is the best source for looking

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:17.760
up known vulnerabilities in both R and Python packages at this point. Once you have that,

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:23.119
you can leverage a feature in Package Manager called Package Blocking,

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:30.079
where instead of taking a bottom-up curated approach to approving every package you want

00:07:30.079 --> 00:07:35.519
to make available, you can instead go top-down and allow the majority of packages available in

00:07:35.519 --> 00:07:41.519
the public repositories, giving your users the most compatibility with everything that's out there,

00:07:41.519 --> 00:07:47.119
but still blocking the ones that have known vulnerabilities and even for blocking packages

00:07:47.119 --> 00:07:52.799
that may have open source licenses that you don't want to make available inside your organization.

00:07:52.959 --> 00:07:57.760
Now, separate from the security risks in the packages themselves, there are a couple more

00:07:57.760 --> 00:08:02.559
malicious risks that prey on weaknesses in the infrastructure that is used to distribute these

00:08:02.559 --> 00:08:09.359
packages. We group these into a category called Package Confusion, which in simplest terms is all

00:08:09.359 --> 00:08:15.200
about deceiving the user into installing the wrong package. So instead of getting the package they

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:20.239
want to use, they are tricked into installing a malicious package that they don't. The type of

00:08:20.399 --> 00:08:26.000
malicious package that they don't. The two risks we'll talk about today are typo squatting and

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:30.399
dependency confusion, which are some of the more common ones and most high-profile ones that we've

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:38.559
seen in the last year. So I'm going to start and give some examples in terms of Python packages,

00:08:38.559 --> 00:08:44.400
as due to that more permissive nature of PyPI, these have shown up in high-profile real-world

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:50.479
exploits in the past year. But the same cases can apply to our package repositories as well.

00:08:52.080 --> 00:08:57.359
So first, let's learn about typo squatting. And let's start with you, the data scientist or

00:08:57.359 --> 00:09:08.880
developer. And we're sitting at our local machine. And you, let's say we want to start a machine

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:15.760
learning project. And so you want to grab your TensorFlow package from PyPI. You use the standard

00:09:15.760 --> 00:09:21.359
Python installation utility pip and say pip install TensorFlow, which is the command to

00:09:21.359 --> 00:09:27.039
install TensorFlow, equivalent to doing install.packages and R to install a package from

00:09:27.679 --> 00:09:35.119
CRAN. And so pip goes out to PyPI, looks for a package called TensorFlow, downloads it,

00:09:35.119 --> 00:09:42.479
installs it into your environment. Perfect. Everything's fine. But now let's start again,

00:09:42.479 --> 00:09:48.960
back in our clean environment. We've still got PyPI there, but this time when we try to install

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:55.760
TensorFlow, we accidentally make a typo and had two Ns in the name of the package. So we have pip

00:09:55.760 --> 00:10:01.760
install TensorFlow with two Ns. Pip goes out and looks for it on PyPI and can't find a package by

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:08.000
that name and returns an error. You notice you mistyped the name, fix it and try again. All is

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.479
well. That's what you expect to happen in those situations and nothing inherently wrong with that.

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:20.159
But here's where things get scary. So let's go back to our clean environment here. And let's say

00:10:20.159 --> 00:10:27.200
that some evil person, try up to no good, looks at the most popular public packages on PyPI.

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:33.760
Like TensorFlow, which, for example, gets downloaded from PyPI on average about 600,000

00:10:33.760 --> 00:10:39.599
times a day globally. And so they take that and they write their own malicious package

00:10:39.599 --> 00:10:46.400
and upload it to PyPI with a bunch of different similar names that are common things that you

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:52.000
might make type by accident if you were trying to install the actual TensorFlow package.

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:57.440
So now we let's take our same scenario. We try to install TensorFlow with two Ns in it

00:10:57.440 --> 00:11:01.119
and make the same typo as before, but instead of getting an error this time,

00:11:01.119 --> 00:11:05.599
pip goes out to PyPI and finds this malicious version that someone put there

00:11:06.479 --> 00:11:11.679
and with the same name downloads it and we've been exploited now because we've gotten the wrong

00:11:11.679 --> 00:11:18.880
packaging here. So these are tough to mitigate against, but there are a few things that we can

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:24.559
do. And I should point out again that these are higher risk with PyPI than on CRAN due to the

00:11:24.559 --> 00:11:29.919
more permissive publishing nature we talked about. But one thing working to our advantages in that

00:11:29.919 --> 00:11:35.760
case is that there are many organizations and companies in the Python community watching for

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:40.640
these malicious packages now. So they're identified relatively quickly once they are published,

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:48.400
usually within a few days or less. So the simplest mitigation we can do is just avoid the latest

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:53.359
packages and updates from public repositories and give them time to be discovered, reported,

00:11:53.359 --> 00:11:59.359
and blocked or removed. And so latest isn't always the safest there, and sometimes it's

00:11:59.359 --> 00:12:05.760
worth it to sacrifice a bit of cutting edge and compatibility in the name of security.

00:12:06.880 --> 00:12:12.559
So in Package Manager, we can leverage what we call repository snapshots to easily pin our

00:12:12.559 --> 00:12:20.320
installation source to a slightly older versions of the repositories. We also get the added benefit

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:25.119
of reproducibility of our projects by not always getting updates to the packages that might break

00:12:25.119 --> 00:12:30.159
our existing code. And it's not a perfect solution, but it's one tool that can be used together with

00:12:30.159 --> 00:12:37.200
these other strategies we're talking about to reduce our risks. Finally, I want to talk about

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:42.880
a different variant that preys particularly on larger teams, especially those who develop and

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:47.679
share their own internal packages to supplement their work that we call dependency confusion.

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:53.039
So let's go back into our clean environment here, where we're now part of a larger company that has

00:12:53.039 --> 00:12:59.039
its own internal packages. Let's say we're at Posit, and we have our internal Posit tools

00:12:59.039 --> 00:13:04.960
package that we use, along with some public packages from PyPI. We may even be so sophisticated

00:13:04.960 --> 00:13:11.440
as to have our own internal packages in a PyPI-like repository so that Pip can install from there.

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:19.760
So we want to install Posit tools. We add this extra index URL flag to our internal server

00:13:21.679 --> 00:13:28.159
so that it can find where our additional packages are. In reality, this extra index URL setting is

00:13:28.159 --> 00:13:33.039
probably set as part of our system configuration, so we don't have to remember to type it every time

00:13:33.039 --> 00:13:38.559
we install something, but I include this here because this is exactly what would actually happen

00:13:38.559 --> 00:13:45.679
in reality. So let's say Pip goes out, looks for a Posit tools package on PyPI, doesn't find it,

00:13:45.679 --> 00:13:51.440
realizes it's not there, so it's probably an internal package, and then searches the extra

00:13:51.440 --> 00:14:00.080
index URL, finds it on our internal repository, and installs it. I also need pandas, so I do the

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:05.359
same command, but in this time, it does find it on PyPI and installs it just as expected.

00:14:05.919 --> 00:14:10.559
So everything's perfect until our malicious actor steps in.

00:14:12.479 --> 00:14:18.880
So an evildoer is targeting Posit employees, for example, and maybe guesses that we probably have

00:14:18.880 --> 00:14:25.119
an internal package named Posit tools that's not available on PyPI. A lot of companies have

00:14:25.119 --> 00:14:30.799
internal packages like this for connecting to internal resources, databases, or other internal

00:14:30.799 --> 00:14:38.640
sources, and so this malicious actor creates their own malicious package and gives it a name they

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:44.400
think that our company might use internally, like Posit tools, and they publish it on PyPI,

00:14:44.960 --> 00:14:50.239
probably with a large version number, in this case like 9.0, so it looks newer than anything else.

00:14:51.200 --> 00:14:56.320
And now we go back to our user who's trying to, say, upgrade Posit tools they have installed,

00:14:56.320 --> 00:15:05.119
and so they, same as before, have their extra index URL, and PIP goes out, and it sees this

00:15:05.119 --> 00:15:10.000
newer version of Posit tools, not from our internal repository, but available now on PyPI,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:13.679
and it doesn't know any better, assumes that's what you want, and installs it,

00:15:14.320 --> 00:15:20.960
and you've been exploited. So, you know, there's lots of variants of this, not just directly

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:24.960
installing packages, but these packages being dependencies of other packages, and all of this

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:32.080
can happen in a similar way here. So this one's actually great because Posit package manager can

00:15:32.080 --> 00:15:38.799
completely insulate you from this case using a unified local and public repository. So in that

00:15:38.799 --> 00:15:44.640
case, we put all of our packages, access all of our packages through package manager, we put our

00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:50.000
internal packages in front of the public package repository, and present that to the user as a

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:56.960
single repository, taking that decision of which package to install completely out of PIP's hands.

00:15:56.960 --> 00:16:02.159
So now when we ask PIP to install Posit tools from our repository here, again,

00:16:02.159 --> 00:16:07.039
it's probably been pre-configured, so we don't have to add the package manager address directly,

00:16:07.039 --> 00:16:13.520
but there's only one that PIP knows to pull things from there. And so PIP goes out,

00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:18.960
asks package manager now, I need the Posit tools package, and package manager knows, hey,

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:23.840
I'm always going to give you the internal one, and because I know that the internal package

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:29.679
supersedes the public one, and I will never ever serve you the public package, and our

00:16:30.239 --> 00:16:37.520
case is solved. Similarly, using the same server, I asked for pandas, pandas is not in our internal

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:42.880
package source, so package manager says, okay, here you go, here's the public one from PIPI,

00:16:43.440 --> 00:16:47.760
and still taking advantage of all of the other security measures that we can also use,

00:16:48.640 --> 00:16:54.880
the curated package blocking or even repository snapshots can all be used in conjunction with

00:16:54.880 --> 00:17:03.359
these local and public repository can unify. Everyone's happy, and we've solved at least one

00:17:03.359 --> 00:17:11.199
of many security risks that we have to worry about. But in summary, the reality is we can't

00:17:11.199 --> 00:17:18.160
deny that public packages do present risks, but really understanding those risks gives you

00:17:18.160 --> 00:17:22.319
the knowledge to manage them. Today, we've talked about some of those strategies,

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:27.199
and how tools like Posit Package Manager can help you reduce some of those risks.

00:17:29.439 --> 00:17:33.199
And for those of you interested in learning more about Posit Package Manager,

